{"title":"Pur","link":"/en/wol/d/r1/lp-e/1200003584","html":"<span id=\"page715\" class=\"pageNum\" data-no=\"715\" data-before-text=\"715\"></span><strong>PUR</strong>A non-Hebrew word found at <a href=\"/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/0/0\" data-bid=\"1-1\" class=\"b\">Esther 3:7</a> and <a href=\"/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/1/0\" data-bid=\"2-1\" class=\"b\">9:24,</a> <a href=\"/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/2/0\" data-bid=\"3-1\" class=\"b\">26</a>; it means &#x201C;lot&#x201D; (Heb., <em>goh&#xB7;ral&#x2B9;; </em>see <a class=\"it\" href=\"/en/wol/tc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/0\">LOT, I</a>). This is the singular form, the plural being &#x201C;Purim.&#x201D; (<a href=\"/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/3/0\" data-bid=\"4-1\" class=\"b\">Es 9:26,</a><a href=\"/en/wol/bc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/3/1\" data-bid=\"4-2\" class=\"b\"> 28-32</a>) &#x201C;Pur&#x201D; is linked with an Akkadian word, <em>puru, </em>meaning &#x201C;lot.&#x201D; It is the source of the name of the Jewish festival Purim.<wbr>&#x2014;See <a class=\"it\" href=\"/en/wol/tc/r1/lp-e/1200003584/1\">PURIM</a>."}